Author-Name: ARTHUR KORTEWEG 
Title: The Net Benefits to Leverage 
Abstract:
 I estimate the market's valuation of the net benefits to leverage using
 panel data from 1994 to 2004, identified from market values and betas of a
 company's debt and equity. The median firm captures net benefits of up to
 5.5% of firm value. Small and profitable firms have high optimal leverage
 ratios, as predicted by theory, but in contrast to existing empirical
 evidence. Companies are on average slightly underlevered relative to the
 optimal leverage ratio at refinancing. This result is mainly due to zero
 leverage firms. I also look at implications for financial policy. Copyright (c) 2010 the American Finance Association. 
