Author-Name: CATHERINE CASAMATTA 
Author-Name: ALEXANDER GUEMBEL 
Title: Managerial Legacies, Entrenchment, and Strategic Inertia 
Abstract:
 This paper argues that the legacy potential of a firm's strategy is an
 important determinant of CEO compensation, turnover, and strategy change.
 A legacy makes CEO replacement expensive, because firm performance can
 only partially be attributed to a newly employed manager. Boards may
 therefore optimally allow an incumbent to be entrenched. Moreover, when a
 firm changes strategy it is optimal to change the CEO, because the
 incumbent has a vested interest in seeing the new strategy fail. Even
 though CEOs have no specific skills in our model, legacy issues can
 explain the empirical association between CEO and strategy change. Copyright (c) 2010 the American Finance Association. 
